1 Biological interpretation of microarray results

Determining lists of differentially expressed genes is only the first step in microarray analysis. To interpret these lists requires: a) an understanding of cellular pathways b) searching the primary literature for information on candidate genes c) statistical procedures to test for differentially expressed sets of genes

2 Gene set enrichment analysis

In the paper from which this case study was taken, a major goal was to contrast the differences in induced responses of S. nigrum and N. attenuata to M. sexta herbivory. The authors assigned up-regulated genes to particular branches and pathways of plant secondary metabolism (figure 1) and inferred differences in the induction of secondary metabolites in response to herbivory. Often, a detailed knowledge of the function of differentially expressed genes is either not available or to time-consuming to obtain for a large number of genes. In such cases, GENE SET ENRICHMENT TESTS facilitate inferences about biological pathways that differ between samples. In the following, learn how to perform a gene set enrichment test on GENE ONTOLOGIES.

The gene ontology (GO) project (http://www.geneontology.org) has developed three structured controlled vocabularies (ontologies) that describe gene products in terms of their associated BIOLOGICAL PROCESSES, CELLULAR COMPONENTS and MOLECULAR FUNCTIONS. Most microarray raw data files, the ones of this case study being no exception, contain GO annotations for the genes on the microarray.

  1. Open a “.gpr” raw data file in “excel” and have a look at the GO annotations provided in column 63. Some genes have one or more GO terms associated with them while others completely lack GO annotation.
  2. Based on column 63, a GO matrix has been constructed with genes as rows and GO terms as columns. Each cell in this matrix contains a “1” if a gene is associated with a GO term and a “0” if there is no association. One gene can be associated with more than one GO term and one GO term can apply to more than one gene. This matrix is needed to test for up and down regulated GO terms. The file containing the matrix is called “potato_gomatrix.txt” and located in the case study folder.
  3. GO terms consist of a GO identifier (e.g. GO.0009699) and a description (e.g. “phenylpropanoid biosynthetic process”). The file with all GO identifiers and their descriptions is called “find.txt” and located in the case study folder.
  4. In R, open the script called “gse test.R” and follow the instructions in the script.
  5. The enrichment test applied here calculates a z-score for a given gene set and infers the significance value of this z-score against standard normal distribution. A gene set is defined as all genes annotated with a particular GO term.
  6. With the R script you run gene set enrichment tests for each of the three contrasts from lab 1 by using files you have created in lab 1: “1_all.txt”, “2_all.txt” and “3_all.txt”. Open one of them in Excel.
  7. The R script will create three new output files: “1_gse.csv”, “2_gse.csv”, and “3_gse.csv”.
  8. Open “1_gse.csv” and “2_gse.csv” which contain differentially expressed GO germs for M. sexta-induced N. attenuata and M. sexta-induced S. nigrum, respectively. GO terms with positive and negative z-Scores and adjusted p-values indicate up-regulation and down-regulation, respectively.
  9. Note, that GO terms such as “phenylpropanoid biosynthetic process” (GO.0009699) and “aromatic amino acid family biosynthetic process, shikimate pathway” (GO.0016089) are up-regulated in M. sexta-induced N. attenuata (“1_gse.csv”) but not in M. sexta-induced S. nigrum (2_gse.csv). On the other hand, note that GO terms such as “sterol biosynthetic process” (GO.0016126) and “steroid biosynthetic process” (GO.0006694) are up-regulated in M. sexta-induced S. nigrum (2_gse.csv) but not in M. sexta-induced N. attenuata (“1_gse.csv”). This is concordant to the inferences made by the authors through figure 1.

3 Candidate Gene Research

In this section, you will find an example on how to obtain information of differentially expressed genes from databases. Read through the example, and then characterize a differentially expressed gene of your choice in a similar way.

  1. Let“s assume you are interested in genes highly up-regulated in M. sexta-induced S. nigrum. Open the respective list (”2_up.txt“) in Excel and sort after logFC (log fold change, column 10). This can be done by highlighting the entire Excel spread sheet by clicking in its upper left corner and then clicking on data -> sort -> sort by”logFC“. Scroll to the bottom and you will notice three clones of leucine aminopeptidase (clones names: STMDQ06, STMCR61, STMGC30) with high logFC values. Note that these clones are not up-regulated in M. sexta-induced N. attenuata (absent from list”1_up.txt“).

  2. To help you formulating a hypothesis about why leucine aminopeptidase is up-regulated in S. nigrum after M. sexta attack you need to find out as much information as possible about this gene. Start by researching its associated GO terms (GO:0004177, GO:0006508) at the Gene Ontology site (http://www.geneontology.org). GO terms can be found in column 8 of the “2_up.txt” file. The search yields the following:
    • GO:0004177: aminopeptidase activity (catalysis of the hydrolysis of N-terminal amino acid residues in a polypeptide chain)
    • GO:0006508: ATP-dependent proteolysis (The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein by the destruction of the native, active configuration, with the hydrolysis of peptide bonds).
  3. To obtain detailed information on the function of a gene refer to the scientific literature. Go and query either PubMed (http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/) or the Web of Knowledge (Massey -> Library -> Article databases -> Web of Knowledge -> Connect to Web of Knowledge) for “leucine aminopeptidase”. Combine the search term “leucine aminopeptidase” with other search terms to be able to find papers that are helpful in the context of this microarray study. For example, terms such as “plants” (eliminates non-plant entries) or “herbivory” (might show entries where this gene has been researched in the context of herbivory) or “Arabidopsis thaliana” (the model plant of the plant kingdom - many genes have been characterized for this plant) or “Solanum nigrum” (the plant where the gene was up-regulated) or “Solanum tuberosum” (the plant that the microarray was originally designed for) in combination with “leucine aminopeptidase”.The following 3 citations have been found to contain useful information on “leucine aminopeptidase”:
    • a review by Matsui et al. (Biol Chem. 2006 Dec; 387(12):1535-44)
    • a functional study by Hard et al. (New Phytol. 2008 Jul; 179(2):356-65)
    • and Fowler et al. (Plant Cell. 2009 April; 21(4): 1239- 1251).

Below I have listed sections from each paper that contains clues regarding a possible function of leucine aminopeptidase:

Matsui et al. (Biol Chem. 2006 Dec; 387(12):1535-44):

…Although the function of LAP-A is not yet known, it has been postulated that LAP-A may have an antinutritive role in alkaline insect guts. This conclusion is based on the fact that LapA is co-regulated with many genes conferring antinutritive properties to foliage (Chao et al.,1999), that LAP-A is exceptionally stable in the alkaline lepidopteran gut (Chen et al., 2005), and that LAP-A has an alkaline pH optimum (Gu et al., 1999). A direct role for LAP-A in defense is consistent with the role of endopeptidases in insect deterrence and defense (Pechan et al., 2002).

Hard et al. (New Phytol. 2008 Jul; 179(2):356-65):

…The LAPs belong to the metallopeptidases and hydrolyse residues at the N-terminus of peptides or proteins (for a recent review see Matsui et al., 2006). They constitute a diverse group of proteins occurring in bacteria, plants, and mammals. In plants, two classes of LAPs are recognized based on their isoelectric point (pI): LAP-N (neutral) and LAP-A (acidic). The former seems to be ubiquitous for angiosperms, being constitutively expressed in most tissues, whereas LAP-A is probably restricted to a group within the Solanaceae to which S. nigrum also belongs (Chao et al., 2000) and accumulates in response to wounding, herbivory, pathogen attack, salt stress and water deficiency (Matsui et al., 2006)…

…The function of plant LAPs is still under discussion and it is likely that the different classes play various roles. Although LAPs were initially classified according to their proteolytic properties, they may act as transcriptional regulators, as has been suggested for microbial LAPs (Matsui et al., 2006). Given that LAP activity increases after herbivory (Gu et al., 1996; Chao et al., 1999) and that it is highly abundant and stable in the insect midgut (Chen et al., 2005), two explanations for the defensive function of LAPs are possible. (1) Leucine aminopeptidase serves as a direct defense in the insect midgut either by damaging it, as shown for a cysteine protease from maize (Pechan et al., 2002), or by reducing the availability of free amino acids through liberation of arginine from peptides and its subsequent degradation by threonine deaminase (Chen et al., 2005). (2) Leucine aminopeptidase acts as a transcriptional or post translational regulator of the jasmonic-acid-mediated signaling cascade and thus influences the overall defense response of the plant, as suggested by Walling (2006) and Matsui et al. (2006)…

…Publicly available microarray data of LAP-A-silenced tomato plants (Walling, TIGR Solanaceae Genomics Resource: http://www.tigr.org/tdb/sol/sol_expression.shtml) point to a regulatory role of LAP late in the JA signaling cascade. By contrast, the relatively slow but steady increase in LAP activity after wounding and herbivore attack and the findings of Chen et al. (2005) concerning stability and abundance in the insect gut make a direct defensive function plausible. To conclude, plant LAPs seem able to contribute to plant defense on multiple levels and are likely not restricted to a single function…

Fowler et al. (Plant Cell. 2009 April; 21(4): 1239- 1251):

Leucine aminopeptidase A (LapA) is a late wound-response gene of tomato (Solanum lycopersicum). To elucidate the role of LapA, transgenic plants that overexpressed or abolished LapA gene expression were used. The early wound-response gene RNA levels were similar in wild-type and Lap-silenced (LapA-SI), -antisense (LapA-AS), and -overexpressing (LapA-OX) plants. By contrast, late wound-response gene RNA levels and protection against Manduca sexta damage were influenced by LapA RNA and protein levels. While LapA-OX plants had elevated levels of LapA RNAs and protein, ectopic expression of LapA was not sufficient to induce Pin (Ser proteinase inhibitor) or PPO (polyphenol oxidase) transcripts in nonwounded leaves. M. sexta larvae damaged less foliage and displayed delays in growth and development when feeding on LapA-OX plants. By contrast, LapA-SI and LapA-AS lines had lower levels of Pin and PPO RNAs than wild-type controls. Furthermore, larvae consumed more foliage and attained larger masses when feeding on LapA-SI plants. Jasmonic acid (JA) did not complement the wound-signaling phenotype of LapA-SI plants. Based on root elongation in the presence of JA, JA perception appeared to be intact in LapA-SI lines. Collectively, these data suggested that LAP-A has a role in modulating essential defenses against herbivores by promoting late wound responses and acting downstream of JA biosynthesis and perception.

  1. Finally, you would like to write a brief synthesis of what you have learned about LAP and discuss this in the light of its up-regulation in S. nigrum plants. The paragraph below is an example of how such a synthesis might look like.

LAP is enzyme that catalyses the hydrolysis of N-terminal amino acid residues in polypeptides and is involved in ATP-dependent proteolysis. LAP may have several roles in the plant“s defense against herbivory. Its exceptional stability in the alkaline lepidopteran gut and co-regulation with antinutritive genes suggest this enzyme to interfere with digestion in the insect gut (Matsui et al. 2006). Other evidence suggests LAP to be involved into wound-signalling - acting downstream of jasmonic acid biosynthesis - and promoting late wound responses in plants (Hard et al. 2008; Fowler et al. 2009). The fact that it is only up-regulated in S. nigrum but not N. attenuata may indicate that either N. attenuata has no LAP orthologue or if it does, it does not respond to herbivory in this plant. The latter would suggest that S. nigrum has evolved a different set of defense responses than N. attenuata.

References:

Fowler JH, Narvaez-Vasquez J, Aromdee DN, et al. (2009) Leucine Aminopeptidase Regulates Defense and Wound Signaling in Tomato Downstream of Jasmonic Acid. Plant Cell, 21, 1239- 1251.

Hard M, Merker H, Schmidt DD, Baldwin IT (2008) Optimized virus-induced gene silencing in Solanum nigrum reveals the defensive function of leucine aminopeptidase against herbivores and the shortcomings of empty vector controls. New Phytol, 179, 356- 365.

Matsui M, Fowler JH, Walling LL (2006) Leucine aminopeptidases: diversity in structure and function. Biological Chemistry, 387, 1535- 1544.
